# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: subtyping-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:subtyping-theory/bounded-quantification] In type theory, **bounded quantification** (also **bounded polymorphism** or **constrained genericity**) refers to universal or existential quantifiers which are restricted ("bounded") to range only over the subtypes of a particular type.
[src:subtyping-theory/bounded-quantification] Bounded quantification is an interaction of parametric polymorphism with subtyping.
[src:subtyping-theory/bounded-quantification] Bounded quantification has traditionally been studied in the functional setting of System F<:, but is available in modern object-oriented languages supporting parametric polymorphism (generics) such as Java, C# and Scala.
[src:subtyping-theory/bounded-quantification] The purpose of bounded quantification is to allow for polymorphic functions to depend on some specific behaviour of objects instead of type inheritance.
[src:subtyping-theory/bounded-quantification] It assumes a record-based model for object classes, where every class member is a record element and all class members are named functions.
[src:subtyping-theory/bounded-quantification] Object attributes are represented as functions that take no argument and return an object.
[src:subtyping-theory/bounded-quantification] The specific behaviour is then some function name along with the types of the arguments and the return type.
[src:subtyping-theory/bounded-quantification] Bounded quantification considers all objects with such a function.
[src:subtyping-theory/bounded-quantification] An example would be a polymorphic `min` function that considers all objects that are comparable to each other.
[src:subtyping-theory/bounded-quantification] This kind of type constraint can be expressed in Java with a generic interface.
[src:subtyping-theory/bounded-quantification] The following example demonstrates how to describe types that can be compared to each other and use this as typing information in polymorphic functions.
[src:subtyping-theory/bounded-quantification] The `Test::min` function uses simple bounded quantification and does not ensure the objects are mutually comparable, in contrast with the `Test::fMin` function which uses F-bounded quantification.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In computer programming, **type variance** is the relationship between subtypes of a composite type (e.g.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] `List[Int]`) and the subtypes of its components (e.g.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] A language's chosen variance determines the relationship between, for example, a list of `Cat`s and a list of `Animal`s, or a function returning `Cat` and a function returning `Animal`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] If the type `Cat` is a subtype of `Animal`, then an expression of type `Cat` should be substitutable wherever an expression of type `Animal` is used.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Depending on the variance of the type constructor, the subtyping relation of the simple types may be either preserved, reversed, or ignored for the respective complex types.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In many programming languages, for example, "list of Cat" will be a subtype of "list of Animal", because the list type constructor is **covariant**.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] This means that the subtyping relation of the simple types is preserved for the complex types.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] On the other hand, "function from Animal to String" is a subtype of "function from Cat to String" because the function type constructor is **contravariant** in the parameter type.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Here, the subtyping relation of the simple types is reversed for the complex types.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] A programming language designer will consider variance when devising typing rules for language features such as arrays, inheritance, and generic datatypes.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] By making type constructors covariant or contravariant instead of invariant, more programs will be accepted as well-typed.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] On the other hand, programmers often find contravariance unintuitive, and accurately tracking variance to avoid runtime type errors can lead to complex typing rules.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In order to keep the type system simple and allow useful programs, a language may treat a type constructor as invariant even if it would be safe to consider it variant, or treat it as covariant even though that could violate type safety.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] These terms come from the notion of covariant and contravariant functors in category theory.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Consider the category C whose objects are types and whose morphisms represent the subtype relationship ≤.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] (This is an example of how any partially ordered set can be considered as a category.) Then for example the function type constructor takes two types *p* and *r* and creates a new type *p* → *r*; so it takes objects in $C^{2}$ to objects in C .
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] By the subtyping rule for function types this operation reverses ≤ for the first parameter and preserves it for the second, so it is a contravariant functor in the first parameter and a covariant functor in the second.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Suppose `A` and `B` are types, and `I<U>` denotes application of a type constructor `I` with type argument `U`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The article considers how this applies to some common type constructors.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The variance of a C# generic interface is declared by placing the `out` (covariant) or `in` (contravariant) attribute on (zero or more of) its type parameters.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The above interfaces are declared as `IEnumerable<out T>`, `Action<in T>`, and `IList<T>`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Types with more than one type parameter may specify different variances on each type parameter.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] For example, the delegate type `Func<in T, out TResult>` represents a function with a **contravariant** input parameter of type `T` and a **covariant** return value of type `TResult`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The compiler checks that all types are defined and used consistently with their annotations, and otherwise signals a compilation error.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The typing rules for interface variance ensure type safety.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] For example, an `Action<T>` represents a first-class function expecting an argument of type `T`, and a function that can handle any type of animal can always be used instead of one that can only handle cats.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Read-only data types (sources) can be covariant; write-only data types (sinks) can be contravariant.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Mutable data types which act as both sources and sinks should be invariant.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] To illustrate this general phenomenon, consider the array type.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] For the type `Animal` we can make the type `Animal[]`, which is an "array of animals".
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] For the purposes of this example, this array supports both reading and writing elements.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] If we wish to avoid type errors, then only the third choice is safe.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Clearly, not every `Animal[]` can be treated as if it were a `Cat[]`, since a client reading from the array will expect a `Cat`, but an `Animal[]` may contain e.g. a `Dog`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Conversely, a `Cat[]` cannot be treated as an `Animal[]`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] It should always be possible to put a `Dog` into an `Animal[]`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] With covariant arrays this cannot be guaranteed to be safe, since the backing store might actually be an array of cats.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] So, the covariant rule is also not safe—the array constructor should be *invariant*.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Note that this is only an issue for mutable arrays; the covariant rule is safe for immutable (read-only) arrays.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Likewise, the contravariant rule would be safe for write-only arrays.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Early versions of Java and C# did not include generics, also termed parametric polymorphism.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In such a setting, making arrays invariant rules out useful polymorphic programs.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] For example, consider writing a function to shuffle an array, or a function that tests two arrays for equality using the `Object`.`equals` method on the elements.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The implementation does not depend on the exact type of element stored in the array, so it should be possible to write a single function that works on all types of arrays.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] However, if array types were treated as invariant, it would only be possible to call these functions on an array of exactly the type `Object[]`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] One could not, for example, shuffle an array of strings.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Therefore, both Java and C# treat array types covariantly.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] For instance, in Java `String[]` is a subtype of `Object[]`, and in C# `string[]` is a subtype of `object[]`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] As discussed above, covariant arrays lead to problems with writes into the array.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Java and C# deal with this by marking each array object with a type when it is created.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Each time a value is stored into an array, the execution environment will check that the run-time type of the value is equal to the run-time type of the array.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In the above example, one can *read* from the array (b) safely.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] It is only trying to *write* to the array that can lead to trouble.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] One drawback to this approach is that it leaves the possibility of a run-time error that a stricter type system could have caught at compile-time.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Also, it hurts performance because each write into an array requires an additional run-time check.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] With the addition of generics, Java and C# now offer ways to write this kind of polymorphic function without relying on covariance.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Alternatively, to enforce that a C# method accesses a collection in a read-only way, one can use the interface `IEnumerable<object>` instead of passing it an array `object[]`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Languages with first-class functions have function types like "a function expecting a Cat and returning an Animal" (written `cat -> animal` in OCaml syntax or `Func<Cat, Animal>` in C# syntax).
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Those languages also need to specify when one function type is a subtype of another—that is, when it is safe to use a function of one type in a context that expects a function of a different type.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] It is safe to substitute a function *f* for a function *g* if *f* accepts a more general type of argument and returns a more specific type than *g*.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] For example, functions of type `animal -> cat`, `cat -> cat`, and `animal -> animal` can be used wherever a `cat -> animal` was expected.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In other words, the → type constructor is *contravariant in the parameter (input) type* and *covariant in the return (output) type*.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] This rule was first stated formally by John C.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Reynolds, and further popularized in a paper by Luca Cardelli.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] When dealing with functions that take functions as arguments, this rule can be applied several times.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In other words, the type $((A\to B)\to C)$ is *covariant* in the position of A .
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] For complicated types it can be confusing to mentally trace why a given type specialization is or isn't type-safe, but it is easy to calculate which positions are co- and contravariant: a position is covariant if it is on the left side of an even number of arrows applying to it.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In an object-oriented programming (OOP) language, when a subclass overrides a method in a superclass, the compiler must check that the overriding method has the right type.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] While some languages require that the type exactly matches the type in the superclass (invariance), it is also type safe to allow the overriding method to have a "better" type.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] By the usual subtyping rule for function types, this means that the overriding method should return a more specific type (return type covariance) and accept a more general argument (parameter type contravariance).
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] For a concrete example, suppose we are writing a class to model an animal shelter.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Now the question is: if we subclass `AnimalShelter`, what types are we allowed to give to `getAnimalForAdoption` and `putAnimal`?
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Among mainstream OOP languages, Java, C++ and C# (as of version 9.0 ) support covariant return types.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Adding the covariant return type was one of the first modifications of the C++ language approved by the standards committee in 1998.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Scala and D also support covariant return types.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Only a few object-oriented languages actually allow this (for example, Python when typechecked with mypy).
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] C++, Java and most other languages that support overloading and/or shadowing would interpret this as a method with an overloaded or shadowed name.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] However, Sather supported both covariance and contravariance.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Calling convention for overridden methods are covariant with *out* parameters and return values, and contravariant with normal parameters (with the mode *in*).
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] A couple of mainstream languages, Eiffel and Dart allow the parameters of an overriding method to have a *more* specific type than the method in the superclass (parameter type covariance).
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] By up-casting a `CatShelter` to an `AnimalShelter`, one can try to place a dog in a cat shelter.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] That does not meet `CatShelter` parameter restrictions and will result in a runtime error.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The lack of type safety (known as the "catcall problem" in the Eiffel community, where "cat" or "CAT" is a Changed Availability or Type) has been a long-standing issue.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Over the years, various combinations of global static analysis, local static analysis, and new language features have been proposed to remedy it, and these have been implemented in some Eiffel compilers.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Despite the type safety problem, the Eiffel designers consider covariant parameter types crucial for modeling real world requirements.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The cat shelter illustrates a common phenomenon: it is *a kind of* animal shelter but has *additional restrictions*, and it seems reasonable to use inheritance and restricted parameter types to model this.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In proposing this use of inheritance, the Eiffel designers reject the Liskov substitution principle, which states that objects of subclasses should always be less restricted than objects of their superclass.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] One other instance of a mainstream language allowing covariance in method parameters is PHP in regards to class constructors.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In the following example, the __construct() method is accepted, despite the method parameter being covariant to the parent's method parameter.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Another example where covariant parameters seem helpful is so-called binary methods, i.e. methods where the parameter is expected to be of the same type as the object the method is called on.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] An example is the `compareTo` method: `a.compareTo(b)` checks whether `a` comes before or after `b` in some ordering, but the way to compare, say, two rational numbers will be different from the way to compare two strings.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Other common examples of binary methods include equality tests, arithmetic operations, and set operations like subset and union.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The drawback of this is that the method is specified to take an argument of type `Object`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In a language with covariant parameters, the argument to `compareTo` could be directly given the desired type `RationalNumber`, hiding the typecast.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Other language features can provide the apparent benefits of covariant parameters while preserving Liskov substitutability.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In a language with *generics* (a.k.a. parametric polymorphism) and bounded quantification, the previous examples can be written in a type-safe way.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Instead of defining `AnimalShelter`, we define a parameterized class `Shelter<T>`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Another language feature that can help is *multiple dispatch*.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] One reason that binary methods are awkward to write is that in a call like `a.compareTo(b)`, selecting the correct implementation of `compareTo` really depends on the runtime type of both `a` and `b`, but in a conventional OO language only the runtime type of `a` is taken into account.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In a language with Common Lisp Object System (CLOS)-style multiple dispatch, the comparison method could be written as a generic function where both arguments are used for method selection.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Giuseppe Castagna observed that in a typed language with multiple dispatch, a generic function can have some parameters which control dispatch and some "left-over" parameters which do not.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Because the method selection rule chooses the most specific applicable method, if a method overrides another method, then the overriding method will have more specific types for the controlling parameters.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] On the other hand, to ensure type safety the language still must require the left-over parameters to be at least as general.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Using the previous terminology, types used for runtime method selection are covariant while types not used for runtime method selection of the method are contravariant.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Conventional single-dispatch languages like Java also obey this rule: only one argument is used for method selection (the receiver object, passed along to a method as the hidden argument `this`), and indeed the type of `this` is more specialized inside overriding methods than in the superclass.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Castagna suggests that examples where covariant parameter types are superior (particularly, binary methods) should be handled using multiple dispatch; which is naturally covariant.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] However, most programming languages do not support multiple dispatch.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The following table summarizes the rules for overriding methods in the languages discussed above.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In programming languages that support generics (a.k.a. parametric polymorphism), the programmer can extend the type system with new constructors.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] For example, a C# interface like `IList<T>` makes it possible to construct new types like `IList<Animal>` or `IList<Cat>`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The question then arises what the variance of these type constructors should be.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In languages with *declaration-site variance annotations* (e.g., C#), the programmer annotates the definition of a generic type with the intended variance of its type parameters.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] With *use-site variance annotations* (e.g., Java), the programmer instead annotates the places where a generic type is instantiated.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The most popular languages with declaration-site variance annotations are C# and Kotlin (using the keywords `out` and `in`), and Scala and OCaml (using the keywords `+` and `-`).
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] C# only allows variance annotations for interface types, while Kotlin, Scala and OCaml allow them for both interface types and concrete data types.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In C#, each type parameter of a generic interface can be marked covariant (`out`), contravariant (`in`), or invariant (no annotation).
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] For example, we can define an interface `IEnumerator<T>` of read-only iterators, and declare it to be covariant (out) in its type parameter.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] With this declaration, `IEnumerator` will be treated as covariant in its type parameter, e.g.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] `IEnumerator<Cat>` is a subtype of `IEnumerator<Animal>`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The type checker enforces that each method declaration in an interface only mentions the type parameters in a way consistent with the `in`/`out` annotations.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] That is, a parameter that was declared covariant must not occur in any contravariant positions (where a position is contravariant if it occurs under an odd number of contravariant type constructors).
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] As an example of how these rules apply, consider the `IList<T>` interface.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The parameter type `T` of `Insert` must be valid contravariantly, i.e. the type parameter `T` must not be tagged `out`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Similarly, the result type `IEnumerator<T>` of `GetEnumerator` must be valid covariantly, i.e.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] (since `IEnumerator` is a covariant interface) the type `T` must be valid covariantly, i.e. the type parameter `T` must not be tagged `in`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] This shows that the interface `IList` is not allowed to be marked either co- or contravariant.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In the common case of a generic data structure such as `IList`, these restrictions mean that an `out` parameter can only be used for methods getting data out of the structure, and an `in` parameter can only be used for methods putting data into the structure, hence the choice of keywords.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] C# allows variance annotations on the parameters of interfaces, but not the parameters of classes.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Because fields in C# classes are always mutable, variantly parameterized classes in C# would not be very useful.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] But languages which emphasize immutable data can make good use of covariant data types.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] For example, in all of Scala, Kotlin and OCaml the immutable list type is covariant: `List[Cat]` is a subtype of `List[Animal]`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Scala's rules for checking variance annotations are essentially the same as C#'s.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] However, there are some idioms that apply to immutable datastructures in particular.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] They are illustrated by the following (excerpt from the) definition of the `List[A]` class.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] First, class members that have a variant type must be immutable.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Here, `head` has the type `A`, which was declared covariant (`+`), and indeed `head` was declared as a method (`def`).
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Trying to declare it as a mutable field (`var`) would be rejected as type error.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Second, even if a data structure is immutable, it will often have methods where the parameter type occurs contravariantly.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] For example, consider the method `::` which adds an element to the front of a list.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] However, this would be a type error, because the covariant parameter `A` appears in a contravariant position (as a function parameter).
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] But there is a trick to get around this problem.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] We give `::` a more general type, which allows adding an element of any type `B` as long as `B` is a supertype of `A`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Note that this relies on `List` being covariant, since `this` has type `List[A]` and we treat it as having type `List[B]`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] At first glance it may not be obvious that the generalized type is sound, but if the programmer starts out with the simpler type declaration, the type errors will point out the place that needs to be generalized.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] It is possible to design a type system where the compiler automatically infers the best possible variance annotations for all datatype parameters.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] However, the analysis can get complex for several reasons.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] First, the analysis is nonlocal since the variance of an interface `I` depends on the variance of all interfaces that `I` mentions.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Second, in order to get unique best solutions the type system must allow *bivariant* parameters (which are simultaneously co- and contravariant).
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] And finally, the variance of type parameters should arguably be a deliberate choice by the designer of an interface, not something that just happens.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] For these reasons most languages do very little variance inference.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] C# and Scala do not infer any variance annotations at all.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] OCaml can infer the variance of parameterized concrete datatypes, but the programmer must explicitly specify the variance of abstract types (interfaces).
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The compiler will automatically infer that `T` is contravariant in the first parameter, and covariant in the second.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The programmer can also provide explicit annotations, which the compiler will check are satisfied.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Explicit annotations in OCaml become useful when specifying interfaces.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] For example, the standard library interface `Map.S` for association tables include an annotation saying that the map type constructor is covariant in the result type.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] `cat IntMap.t` is a subtype of `animal IntMap.t`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] One drawback of the declaration-site approach is that many interface types must be made invariant.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] For example, we saw above that `IList` needed to be invariant, because it contained both `Insert` and `GetEnumerator`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In order to expose more variance, the API designer could provide additional interfaces which provide subsets of the available methods (e.g. an "insert-only list" which only provides `Insert`).
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Use-site variance means the desired variance is indicated with an annotation at the specific site in the code where the type will be used.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] This gives users of a class more opportunities for subtyping without requiring the designer of the class to define multiple interfaces with different variance.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Instead, at the point a generic type is instantiated to an actual parameterized type, the programmer can indicate that only a subset of its methods will be used.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In effect, each definition of a generic class also makes available interfaces for the covariant and contravariant *parts* of that class.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Java provides use-site variance annotations through wildcards, a restricted form of bounded existential types.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] A parameterized type can be instantiated by a wildcard `?` together with an upper or lower bound, e.g.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] `List<? extends Animal>` or `List<? super Animal>`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] An unbounded wildcard like `List<?>` is equivalent to `List<? extends Object>`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Such a type represents `List<X>` for some unknown type `X` which satisfies the bound.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] will be rejected as a type error since an `Animal` is not necessarily an `X`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In general, given some interface `I<T>`, a reference to an `I<? extends T>` forbids using methods from the interface where `T` occurs contravariantly in the type of the method.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Conversely, if `l` had type `List<? super Animal>` one could call `l.add` but not `l.get`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] While non-wildcard parameterized types in Java are invariant (e.g. there is no subtyping relationship between `List<Cat>` and `List<Animal>`), wildcard types can be made more specific by specifying a tighter bound.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] For example, `List<? extends Cat>` is a subtype of `List<? extends Animal>`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] This shows that wildcard types are *covariant in their upper bounds* (and also *contravariant in their lower bounds*).
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In total, given a wildcard type like `C<? extends T>`, there are three ways to form a subtype: by specializing the class `C`, by specifying a tighter bound `T`, or by replacing the wildcard `?` with a specific type (see figure).
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] By applying two of the above three forms of subtyping, it becomes possible to, for example, pass an argument of type `List<Cat>` to a method expecting a `List<? extends Animal>`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] This is the kind of expressiveness that results from covariant interface types.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The type `List<? extends Animal>` acts as an interface type containing only the covariant methods of `List<T>`, but the implementer of `List<T>` did not have to define it ahead of time.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In the common case of a generic data structure `IList`, covariant parameters are used for methods getting data out of the structure, and contravariant parameters for methods putting data into the structure.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The mnemonic for Producer Extends, Consumer Super (PECS), from the book *Effective Java* by Joshua Bloch gives an easy way to remember when to use covariance and contravariance.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Wildcards are flexible, but there is a drawback.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] While use-site variance means that API designers need not consider variance of type parameters to interfaces, they must often instead use more complicated method signatures.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] A common example involves the `Comparable` interface.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Suppose we want to write a function that finds the biggest element in a collection.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] However, this type is not general enough—one can find the max of a `Collection<Calendar>`, but not a `Collection<GregorianCalendar>`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The problem is that `GregorianCalendar` does not implement `Comparable<GregorianCalendar>`, but instead the (better) interface `Comparable<Calendar>`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In Java, unlike in C#, `Comparable<Calendar>` is not considered a subtype of `Comparable<GregorianCalendar>`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The bounded wildcard `? super T` conveys the information that `max` calls only contravariant methods from the `Comparable` interface.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] This particular example is frustrating because *all* the methods in `Comparable` are contravariant, so that condition is trivially true.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] A declaration-site system could handle this example with less clutter by annotating only the definition of `Comparable`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Use-site variance annotations provide additional flexibility, allowing more programs to type check.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] However, they have been criticized for the complexity they add to the language, leading to complicated type signatures and error messages.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] One way to assess whether the extra flexibility is useful is to see if it is used in existing programs.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] A survey of a large set of Java libraries found that 39% of wildcard annotations could have been directly replaced by declaration-site annotations.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Thus the remaining 61% is an indication of places where Java benefits from having the use-site system available.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In a declaration-site language, libraries must either expose less variance, or define more interfaces.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] This design works well with declaration-site annotations, but the large number of interfaces carry a complexity cost for clients of the library.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] And modifying the library interface may not be an option—in particular, one goal when adding generics to Java was to maintain binary backwards compatibility.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] On the other hand, Java wildcards are themselves complex.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In a conference presentation Joshua Bloch criticized them as being too hard to understand and use, stating that when adding support for closures "we simply cannot afford another *wildcards*".
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Early versions of Scala used use-site variance annotations but programmers found them difficult to use in practice, while declaration-site annotations were found to be very helpful when designing classes.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Later versions of Scala added Java-style existential types and wildcards; however, according to Martin Odersky, if there were no need for interoperability with Java then these would probably not have been included.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Ross Tate argues that part of the complexity of Java wildcards is due to the decision to encode use-site variance using a form of existential types.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] The original proposals used special-purpose syntax for variance annotations, writing `List<+Animal>` instead of Java's more verbose `List<? extends Animal>`.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Since wildcards are a form of existential types they can be used for more things than just variance.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] A type like `List<?>` ("a list of unknown type") lets objects be passed to methods or stored in fields without exactly specifying their type parameters.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] This is particularly valuable for classes such as `Class` where most of the methods do not mention the type parameter.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] However, type inference for existential types is a difficult problem.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] For the compiler implementer, Java wildcards raise issues with type checker termination, type argument inference, and ambiguous programs.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] In general it is undecidable whether a Java program using generics is well-typed or not, so any type checker will have to go into an infinite loop or time out for some programs.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] For the programmer, it leads to complicated type error messages.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Java type checks wildcard types by replacing the wildcards with fresh type variables (so-called *capture conversion*).
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] This can make error messages harder to read, because they refer to type variables that the programmer did not directly write.
[src:subtyping-theory/covariance-and-contravariance-computer-science] Since both declaration-site and use-site annotations can be useful, some type systems provide both.
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] The **Liskov substitution principle** (**LSP**) is a particular definition of a subtyping relation, called strong behavioral subtyping, that was initially introduced by Barbara Liskov in a 1987 conference keynote address titled *Data abstraction and hierarchy*.
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] It is based on the concept of "substitutability" – a principle in object-oriented programming stating that an object of a superclass may be replaced by an object of a subclass without breaking the program.
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] It is a semantic rather than merely syntactic relation, because it intends to guarantee semantic interoperability of types in a hierarchy, object types in particular.
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] Symbolically: ${\texttt {S}}\leq {\texttt {T}}\to (\forall x{:}{\texttt {T}}.\phi (x)\to \forall y{:}{\texttt {S}}.\phi (y))$ That is, if S subtypes T, what holds for T-objects holds for S-objects.
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] In the same paper, Liskov and Wing detailed their notion of behavioral subtyping in an extension of Hoare logic, which bears a certain resemblance to Bertrand Meyer's design by contract in that it considers the interaction of subtyping with preconditions, postconditions and invariants.
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] Liskov's notion of a behavioural subtype defines a notion of substitutability for objects; that is, if `S` is a subtype of `T`, then objects of type `T` in a program may be replaced with objects of type `S` without altering any of the desirable properties of that program (e.g. correctness).
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] Behavioural subtyping is a stronger notion than typical subtyping of functions defined in type theory, which relies only on the contravariance of parameter types and covariance of the return type.
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] Behavioural subtyping is undecidable in general: if `q` is the property "method for `x` always terminates", then it is impossible for a program (e.g. a compiler) to verify that it holds true for some subtype `S` of `T`, even if `q` does hold for `T`.
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] Nonetheless, the principle is useful in reasoning about the design of class hierarchies.
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] In addition to the signature requirements, the subtype must meet a number of behavioural conditions.
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] The rules on pre- and postconditions are identical to those introduced by Bertrand Meyer in his 1988 book *Object-Oriented Software Construction*.
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] Both Meyer, and later Pierre America, who was the first to use the term *behavioral subtyping*, gave proof-theoretic definitions of some behavioral subtyping notions, but their definitions did not take into account aliasing that may occur in programming languages that support references or pointers.
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] Taking aliasing into account was the major improvement made by Liskov and Wing (1994), and a key ingredient is the history constraint.
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] Under the definitions of Meyer and America, a mutable point would be a behavioral subtype of an immutable point, whereas Liskov substitution principle forbids this.
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] Liskov substitution principle explains a property, *"If for each object `o1` of type `S` there is an object `o2` of type `T` such that for all programs `P` defined in terms of `T`, the behavior of `P` is unchanged when `o1` is substituted for `o2` then `S` is a subtype of `T`,"*.
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] From a programming point of view, the `Square` class may be defined as extending the `Rectangle` class.
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] However, this violates LSP even though the is-a relationship holds between `Rectangle` and `Square`.
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] Consider the following example, where function `g` does not work if a `Square` is passed in, and so the open-closed principle might be considered to have been violated.
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] Conversely, if one considers that the type of a shape should only be a constraint on the relationship of its dimensions, then the assumption in `g()` that `setHeight()` will change height, and area, but not width is invalid.
[src:subtyping-theory/liskov-substitution-principle] This assumption is invalid not only for squares, but even potentially for other rectangles that might be coded to preserve area or aspect ratio when height changes.
[src:subtyping-theory/nominal-type-system] In computer science, a type system is **nominal** (also called **nominative** or **name-based**) if compatibility and equivalence of data types is determined by explicit declarations and/or the name of the types.
[src:subtyping-theory/nominal-type-system] Nominal systems are used to determine whether types are equivalent, as well as whether a type is a subtype of another.
[src:subtyping-theory/nominal-type-system] Nominal type systems contrast with *structural systems*, where comparisons are based on the structure of the types in question and do not require explicit declarations.
[src:subtyping-theory/nominal-type-system] Nominal typing means that two variables are type-compatible if and only if their declarations name the same type.
[src:subtyping-theory/nominal-type-system] For example, in C, two `struct` types with different names in the same translation unit are never considered compatible, even if they have identical field declarations.
[src:subtyping-theory/nominal-type-system] However, C also allows a `typedef` declaration, which introduces an alias for an existing type.
[src:subtyping-theory/nominal-type-system] These are merely syntactical and do not differentiate the type from its alias for the purpose of type checking.
[src:subtyping-theory/nominal-type-system] This feature, present in many languages, can result in a loss of type safety when (for example) the same primitive integer type is used in two semantically distinct ways.
[src:subtyping-theory/nominal-type-system] Haskell provides the C-style syntactic alias in the form of the `type` declaration, as well as the `newtype` declaration that does introduce a new, distinct type, isomorphic to an existing type.
[src:subtyping-theory/nominal-type-system] In a similar fashion, **nominal subtyping** means that one type is a subtype of another if and only if it is explicitly declared to be so in its definition.
[src:subtyping-theory/nominal-type-system] Nominally-typed languages typically enforce the requirement that declared subtypes be structurally compatible (though Eiffel allows non-compatible subtypes to be declared).
[src:subtyping-theory/nominal-type-system] However, subtypes which are structurally compatible "by accident", but not declared as subtypes, are not considered to be subtypes.
[src:subtyping-theory/nominal-type-system] C++, C#, Java, Kotlin, Objective-C, Delphi, Swift, Julia and Rust all primarily use both nominal typing and nominal subtyping.
[src:subtyping-theory/nominal-type-system] Some nominally-subtyped languages, such as Java and C#, allow classes to be declared *final* (or *sealed* in C# terminology), indicating that no further subtyping is permitted.
[src:subtyping-theory/nominal-type-system] Nominal typing is useful at preventing accidental type equivalence, which allows better type-safety than structural typing.
[src:subtyping-theory/nominal-type-system] The cost is a reduced flexibility, as, for example, nominal typing does not allow new super-types to be created without modification of the existing subtypes.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] A **structural type system** (or **property-based type system**) is a major class of type systems in which type compatibility and equivalence are determined by the type's actual structure or definition and not by other characteristics such as its name or place of declaration.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] Structural systems are used to determine if types are equivalent and whether a type is a subtype of another.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] It contrasts with *nominative systems*, where comparisons are based on the names of the types or explicit declarations, and *duck typing*, in which only the part of the structure accessed at runtime is checked for compatibility.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] In *structural typing*, an element is considered to be compatible with another if, for each feature within the second element's type, a corresponding and identical feature exists in the first element's type.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] Some languages may differ on the details, such as whether the *features* must match in name.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] This definition is not symmetric, and includes subtype compatibility.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] Two types are considered to be identical if each is compatible with the other.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] For example, OCaml uses structural typing on methods for compatibility of object types.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] Go uses structural typing on methods to determine compatibility of a type with an interface.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] C++ template functions exhibit structural typing on type arguments.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] Haxe uses structural typing, but classes are not structurally subtyped.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] In languages which support subtype polymorphism, a similar dichotomy can be formed based on how the subtype relationship is defined.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] One type is a subtype of another if and only if it contains all the *features* of the base type, or subtypes thereof.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] The subtype may contain added features, such as members not present in the base type, or stronger invariants.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] A distinction exists between structural substitution for inferred and non-inferred polymorphism.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] Some languages, such as Haskell, do not substitute structurally in the case where an expected type is declared (i.e., not inferred), e.g., only substitute for functions that are signature-based polymorphic via type inference.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] Then it is not possible to accidentally subtype a non-inferred type, although it may still be possible to provide an explicit conversion to a non-inferred type, which is invoked implicitly.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] Structural subtyping is arguably more flexible than nominative subtyping, as it permits the creation of *ad hoc* types and protocols; in particular, it permits creation of a type which is a supertype of an existing type, without modifying the definition of the latter.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] However, this may not be desirable where the programmer wishes to create closed abstractions.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] One way this can be avoided is by creating one algebraic data type for each use.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] In 1990, Cook, et al., proved that *inheritance is not subtyping* in structurally-typed OO languages.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] Checking that two types are compatible, based on structural typing, is a non-trivial operation, e.g., requires maintaining a stack of previous checked types.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] When a type does not match the expected structure, error messages are longer than with nominal typing.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] Objects in OCaml are structurally typed by the names and types of their methods.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] Objects can be created directly (*immediate objects*) without going through a nominative class.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] Classes only serve as functions for creating objects.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] Here the OCaml interactive runtime prints out the inferred type of the object for convenience.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] Its type (`< get_x : int; set_x : int -> unit >`) is defined only by its methods.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] In other words, the type of x is defined by the method types "get_x : int" and "set_x : int -> unit" rather than by any name.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] So they must be the same type, or else this wouldn't even type-check.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] This shows that equivalence of types is structural.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] The inferred type for the first argument (`< set_x : int -> 'a; .. >`) is interesting.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] The `..` means that the first argument can be any object which has a "set_x" method, which takes an int as argument.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] This shows that compatibility for things like method invocation is determined by structure.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] The object `x` is not of this type; but structurally, `x` is of a subtype of this type, since `x` contains a superset of its methods.
[src:subtyping-theory/structural-type-system] This shows that compatibility for widening coercions are structural.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] In programming language theory, **subtyping** (also called **subtype polymorphism** or **inclusion polymorphism**) is a form of type polymorphism.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] A ***subtype*** is a datatype that is related to another datatype (the ***supertype***) by some notion of substitutability, meaning that program elements (typically subroutines or functions), written to operate on elements of the supertype, can also operate on elements of the subtype.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] If S is a subtype of T, the subtyping relation (written as *S* <: *T*, *S* ⊑ *T*, or *S* ≤: *T* ) means that any term of type S can *safely be used* in *any context* where a term of type T is expected.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The precise semantics of subtyping here crucially depends on the particulars of how *"safely be used"* and *"any context"* are defined by a given type formalism or programming language.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The type system of a programming language essentially defines its own subtyping relation, which may well be trivial, should the language support no (or very little) conversion mechanisms.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Due to the subtyping relation, a term may belong to more than one type.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Subtyping is therefore a form of type polymorphism.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] In object-oriented programming the term 'polymorphism' is commonly used to refer solely to this *subtype polymorphism*, while the techniques of parametric polymorphism would be considered *generic programming*.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Functional programming languages often allow the subtyping of records.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Consequently, simply typed lambda calculus extended with record types is perhaps the simplest theoretical setting in which a useful notion of subtyping may be defined and studied.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Because the resulting calculus allows terms to have more than one type, it is no longer a "simple" type theory.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Since functional programming languages, by definition, support function literals, which can also be stored in records, records types with subtyping provide some of the features of object-oriented programming.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Typically, functional programming languages also provide some, usually restricted, form of parametric polymorphism.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] In a theoretical setting, it is desirable to study the interaction of the two features; a common theoretical setting is system F<:.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Various calculi that attempt to capture the theoretical properties of object-oriented programming may be derived from system F<:.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The concept of subtyping is related to the linguistic notions of hyponymy and holonymy.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] It is also related to the concept of bounded quantification in mathematical logic (see Order-sorted logic).
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] In a number of object-oriented languages, subtyping is called **interface inheritance**, with inheritance referred to as *implementation inheritance*.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The notion of subtyping in programming languages dates back to the 1960s; it was introduced in Simula derivatives.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The first formal treatments of subtyping were given by John C.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Reynolds in 1980 who used category theory to formalize implicit conversions, and Luca Cardelli (1985).
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The concept of subtyping has gained visibility (and synonymy with polymorphism in some circles) with the mainstream adoption of object-oriented programming.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] In this context, the principle of safe substitution is often called the Liskov substitution principle, after Barbara Liskov who popularized it in a keynote address at a conference on object-oriented programming in 1987.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Because it must consider mutable objects, the ideal notion of subtyping defined by Liskov and Jeannette Wing, called behavioral subtyping is considerably stronger than what can be implemented in a type checker.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] A simple practical example of subtypes is shown in the diagram.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The type "bird" has three subtypes "duck", "cuckoo" and "ostrich".
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Conceptually, each of these is a variety of the basic type "bird" that inherits many "bird" characteristics but has some specific differences.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The UML notation is used in this diagram, with open-headed arrows showing the direction and type of the relationship between the supertype and its subtypes.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] As a more practical example, a language might allow integer values to be used wherever floating point values are expected (`Integer` <: `Float`), or it might define a generic type Number as a common supertype of integers and the reals.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] In this second case, we only have `Integer` <: `Number` and `Float` <: `Number`, but `Integer` and `Float` are not subtypes of each other.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Programmers may take advantage of subtyping to write code in a more abstract manner than would be possible without it.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] If integer and real are both subtypes of `Number`, and an operator of comparison with an arbitrary Number is defined for both types, then values of either type can be passed to this function.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] However, the very possibility of implementing such an operator highly constrains the Number type (for example, one can't compare an integer with a complex number), and actually only comparing integers with integers, and reals with reals, makes sense.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Rewriting this function so that it would only accept 'x' and 'y' of the same type requires bounded polymorphism.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Subtyping enables a given type to be substituted for another type or abstraction.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Subtyping is said to establish an is-a relationship between the subtype and some existing abstraction, either implicitly or explicitly, depending on language support.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The relationship can be expressed explicitly via inheritance in languages that support inheritance as a subtyping mechanism.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The following C++ code establishes an explicit inheritance relationship between classes **B** and **A**, where **B** is both a subclass and a subtype of **A**, and can be used as an **A** wherever a **B** is specified (via a reference, a pointer or the object itself).
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The following python code establishes an explicit inheritance relationship between classes *B* and *A*, where *B* is both a subclass and a subtype of *A*, and can be used as an *A* wherever a *B* is required.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The following example, *type(a)* is a "regular" type, and *type(type(a))* is a metatype.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] While as distributed all types have the same metatype (*PyType_Type*, which is also its own metatype), this is not a requirement.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The type of classic classes, known as *types.ClassType*, can also be considered a distinct metatype.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] In Java, **is-a** relation between the type parameters of one class or interface and the type parameters of another are determined by the extends and implements clauses.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Using the `Collections` classes, `ArrayList<E>` implements `List<E>`, and `List<E>` extends `Collection<E>`.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] So `ArrayList<String>` is a subtype of `List<String>`, which is a subtype of `Collection<String>`.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The subtyping relationship is preserved between the types automatically.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] In type theory the concept of *subsumption* is used to define or evaluate whether a type **S** is a subtype of type **T**.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The set can be described *extensionally* by listing all the values, or it can be described *intensionally* by stating the membership of the set by a predicate over a domain of possible values.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] In common programming languages enumeration types are defined extensionally by listing values.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] User-defined types like records (structs, interfaces) or classes are defined intensionally by an explicit type declaration or by using an existing value, which encodes type information, as a prototype to be copied or extended.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] In discussing the concept of subsumption, the set of values of a type is indicated by writing its name in mathematical italics: T.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The type, viewed as a predicate over a domain, is indicated by writing its name in bold: **T**.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The conventional symbol **<:** means "is a subtype of", and **:>** means "is a supertype of".
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] In terms of information specificity, a subtype is considered more specific than any one of its supertypes, because it holds at least as much information as each of them.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] This may increase the applicability, or *relevance* of the subtype (the number of situations where it can be accepted or introduced), as compared to its "more general" supertypes.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The disadvantage of having this more detailed information is that it represents incorporated choices which reduce the *prevalence* of the subtype (the number of situations which are able to generate or produce it).
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] In the context of subsumption, the type definitions can be expressed using Set-builder notation, which uses a predicate to define a set.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Predicates can be defined over a domain (set of possible values) D.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Predicates are partial functions that compare values to selection criteria.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] For example: "is an integer value greater than or equal to 100 and less than 200?".
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] If a value matches the criteria then the function returns the value.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] If not, the value is not selected, and nothing is returned.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The predicate $\mathbf {T} =P_{T}$ is applied alongside $P_{s}$ as part of the compound predicate **S** defining S.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The two predicates are *conjoined*, so both must be true for a value to be selected.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] For example: there is a subfamily of cat species called *Felinae*, which is part of the family *Felidae*.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The genus *Felis*, to which the domestic cat species *Felis catus* belongs, is part of that subfamily.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The conjunction of predicates has been expressed here through application of the second predicate over the domain of values conforming to the first predicate.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Viewed as types, **Felis <: Felinae <: Felidae**.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] If **T** subsumes **S** (**T :> S**) then a procedure, function or expression given a value $s\in S$ as an operand (parameter value or term) will therefore be able to operate over that value as one of type **T**, because $s\in T$ .
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] In the example above, we could expect the function *ofSubfamily* to be applicable to values of all three types **Felidae**, **Felinae** and **Felis**.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Type theorists make a distinction between **nominal subtyping**, in which only types declared in a certain way may be subtypes of each other, and **structural subtyping**, in which the structure of two types determines whether or not one is a subtype of the other.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] This so-called *duck typing* is common in dynamically typed object-oriented languages.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Sound structural subtyping rules for types other than object types are also well known.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The subtyping induced by subclassing in an object-oriented language is usually inclusive; subtyping relations that relate integers and floating-point numbers, which are represented differently, are usually coercive.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] In almost all type systems that define a subtyping relation, it is reflexive (meaning *A* <: *A* for any type *A*) and transitive (meaning that if *A* <: *B* and *B* <: *C* then *A* <: *C*).
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Types of records give rise to the concepts of *width* and *depth* subtyping.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] These express two different ways of obtaining a new type of record that allows the same operations as the original record type.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Recall that a record is a collection of (named) fields.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Since a subtype is a type which allows all operations allowed on the original type, a record subtype should support the same operations on the fields as the original type supported.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] One kind of way to achieve such support, called *width subtyping*, adds more fields to the record.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] More formally, every (named) field appearing in the width supertype will appear in the width subtype.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Thus, any operation feasible on the supertype will be supported by the subtype.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The second method, called *depth subtyping*, replaces the various fields with their subtypes.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] That is, the fields of the subtype are subtypes of the fields of the supertype.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Since any operation supported for a field in the supertype is supported for its subtype, any operation feasible on the record supertype is supported by the record subtype.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Subtyping of records can be defined in System F<:, which combines parametric polymorphism with subtyping of record types and is a theoretical basis for many functional programming languages that support both features.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Some systems also support subtyping of labeled disjoint union types (such as algebraic data types).
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The rule for width subtyping is reversed: every tag appearing in the width subtype must appear in the width supertype.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] If *T*1 → *T*2 is a function type, then a subtype of it is any function type *S*1 → *S*2 with the property that *T*1 <: *S*1 and *S*2 <: *T*2.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The parameter type of *S*1 → *S*2 is said to be contravariant because the subtyping relation is reversed for it, whereas the return type is covariant.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Informally, this reversal occurs because the refined type is "more liberal" in the types it accepts and "more conservative" in the type it returns.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] In languages that allow side effects, like most object-oriented languages, subtyping is generally not sufficient to guarantee that a function can be safely used in the context of another.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Liskov's work in this area focused on behavioral subtyping, which besides the type system safety discussed in this article also requires that subtypes preserve all invariants guaranteed by the supertypes in some contract.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] This definition of subtyping is generally undecidable, so it cannot be verified by a type checker.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The subtyping of mutable references is similar to the treatment of parameter values and return values.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Write-only references (or *sinks*) are contravariant, like parameter values; read-only references (or *sources*) are covariant, like return values.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Mutable references which act as both sources and sinks are invariant.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Subtyping and inheritance are independent (orthogonal) relationships.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] They may coincide, but none is a special case of the other.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The first case is illustrated by independent types, such as `Boolean` and `Float`.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The second case can be illustrated by the relationship between `Int32` and `Int64`.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] In most object oriented programming languages, `Int64` are unrelated by inheritance to `Int32`.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] However `Int32` can be considered a subtype of `Int64` since any 32 bit integer value can be promoted into a 64 bit integer value.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The third case is a consequence of function subtyping input contravariance.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Assume a super class of type *T* having a method *m* returning an object of the same type (*i.e.* the type of *m* is *T* → *T*, also note that the first parameter of *m* is this/self) and a derived class type *S* from *T*.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] By inheritance, the type of *m* in *S* is *S* → *S*.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] In order for *S* to be a subtype of *T* the type of *m* in *S* must be a subtype of the type of *m* in *T* , in other words: *S* → *S* ≤: *T* → *T*.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] By bottom-up application of the function subtyping rule, this means: *S* ≤: *T* and *T* ≤: *S*, which is only possible if *S* and *T* are the same.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Since inheritance is an irreflexive relation, *S* can't be a subtype of *T*.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Subtyping and inheritance are compatible when all inherited fields and methods of the derived type have types which are subtypes of the corresponding fields and methods from the inherited type .
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] In coercive subtyping systems, subtypes are defined by explicit type conversion functions from subtype to supertype.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] For each subtyping relationship (*S* <: *T*), a coercion function *coerce*: *S* → *T* is provided, and any object *s* of type *S* is regarded as the object *coerce**S* → *T*(*s*) of type *T*.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] A coercion function may be defined by composition: if *S* <: *T* and *T* <: *U* then *s* may be regarded as an object of type *u* under the compound coercion (*coerce**T* → *U* ∘ *coerce**S* → *T*).
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The type coercion from a type to itself *coerce**T* → *T* is the identity function *id*T.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Coercion functions for records and disjoint union subtypes may be defined componentwise; in the case of width-extended records, type coercion simply discards any components which are not defined in the supertype.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The type coercion for function types may be given by *f'*(*t*) = *coerce**S*2 → *T*2(*f*(*coerce**T*1 → *S*1(*t*))), reflecting the contravariance of parameter values and covariance of return values.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] The coercion function is uniquely determined given the subtype and supertype.
[src:subtyping-theory/subtyping] Thus, when multiple subtyping relationships are defined, one must be careful to guarantee that all type coercions are coherent.
